	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="1541328405" id="dsq-comment-1541328405">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-1541328405">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2014-08-13</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-1541328405" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-1541328405" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hi Jasper!</p><p>Yea, that's quite controversial - even William and I disagree on this :). William (who I admit is more knowledgeable than I am) recommends using a single controller for both the HTML and JSON (or XML) representations. The potential problem with this approach might be if your web interface doesn't really look like your API. For example, you might have a /products API endpoint. But perhaps there's really no "products list" web interface page - perhaps instead there is /dashboard only, which shows products and users you're connected to (just imagining some example).</p><p>I would say, if you're comfortable with the idea of using one controller to return different representations, try that. But realize, that you may have some controllers that will only return JSON or will only return HTML, because there is only a JSON version of /products and an HTML version of /dashboard. And I think that's ok :). If you're overwhelmed by all of this, then don't feel bad using different controllers (but do your best to use services to avoid duplication).</p><p>Great question!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
